[[File:Nord Bachelor Circumpolar Studies Diploma.png|thumb|English-language Bachelor of Circumpolar Studies diploma from [[Nord University]]]]
'''Circumpolar studies''' (also ''Northern studies'') is an [[Interdisciplinarity|interdisciplinary]] [[field of study]] combining [[social science]] and [[Earth science|geoscience]] and involving topics like [[land]], [[Natural environment|environment]], [[Ethnic group|peoples]], [[culture]]s, and [[politics]] in [[Arctic]] and [[Subarctic]] [[Arctic Council|states]], that is, the [[United States]] ([[Alaska]]), [[Canada]], [[Denmark]] ([[Greenland]]), [[Iceland]], [[Norway]], [[Sweden]], [[Finland]], and [[Russia]]. Because of circumpolar regions' past as [[Colonization|colonised]] territories inhabited by [[nomad]]s, circumpolar studies focusses on [[Circumpolar peoples|indigenous peoples]] as well as [[Early modern period|early]] [[Agrarian society|agricultural]] [[settler]]s.<ref name="UArctic Circumpolar Studies"/>
== Information == Circumpolar studies is the [[Interdisciplinarity|interdisciplinary]] study of regions located on and above the [[Arctic Circle|polar circle]]. As such, circumpolar studies embraces wider than [[Arctic studies]], which deals with the [[Arctic]] ''[[sensu stricto]]''.
Classified as [[Area studies|regional studies]], circumpolar studies finds a parallel in [[European studies]], [[African studies]], [[Latin American studies]], and so on. Gaining increased prominence in the wake of post-[[Cold War]] initiatives like the [[Arctic Council]], circumpolar studies is maintained as an independent field of study by [[University|universities]] like the [[University of Alaska Fairbanks]] and [[Nord University]] and recognised as ditto by [[Publishing|publishers]] like [[Berghahn Books]].<ref name="UArctic Where to Study"/><ref name="Berghahn Books"/>
Based on a degree model developed by the [[University of the Arctic]], over twenty educational institutions in [[Arctic Circle|circumpolar regions]] offer circumpolar studies at [[Undergraduate degree|undergraduate level]], including [[bachelor's degree]]s and short-term programmes.<ref name="UArctic Where to Study"/> There is also a [[France|French]] university offering circumpolar studies at graduate level.{{Citation needed|date=July 2018}}
The Arctic Centre at the [[University of Groningen]] publishes an eponymous series with biennial volumes,<ref name="UG Circumpolar Series"/> while the ''Journal of Northern Studies'' is published at [[Umeå University]]. Related research centres include the [[Center for Northern Studies]] at Nord University.
